The Prague Stock Exchange crashes into a downturn against business closing.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ’s shares reached almost half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange began trading on Tuesday at the beginning of Monday’s break-in, as it fell by another six percentage points.
This time, the reason was the Wall Street intrusion.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the U.S. House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of stocks in Asia
A dramatic fall occurred on Tuesday in stocks on the Asian stock exchanges, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost almost four percentage points during the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange fell by 3.6 percent, according to the index.
“The timing of rescue action in the United States is uncertain and will affect the financial markets worldwide,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are moving at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the bill to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected by the incursion.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion CZK) should be spent.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw the biggest burglary in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by nearly seven percent, a similar slump it had last seen in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was little indication that the draft would not pass in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress Makes Confession: US Government May Pump $700 Billion into Banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance for the American financial system.
It is expected to be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks on adopting a rescue plan in the form of a $700 billion bailout for the U.S. financial system.
However, this does not yet signify a victory.
Congressmen have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various reports, the plan could probably be voted on in the Senate by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notification that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of the financial markets.
Afterwards, however, there is a "sensitization" due to the complicated mechanisms, how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilise the market should look like," Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to him, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This envisages a purchase of non-sellable mortgage assets from financial corporations, which plunges financial firms into severe losses and jeopardizes the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the market.
We have to continue the recovery plan even further, but I think we are on target," Paulson said.
A Signal for Asian Businesses
The global financial crisis is also striking in the stock markets, which are declining sharply.
According to the words of the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
This is aimed at reassuring investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, and there is uncertainty as to whether the last-minute negotiations could still fail on a problem.
Legislators hope that it will be passed in the next few days.
However, the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has called for.
Congress, however, can block the disbursement of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush Says Progress in Negotiations Positive
The President has a veto on this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was based on obtaining finances for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, has persisted because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The US President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and “appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of golden parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the monetary program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding concessions, and a timeline for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
This should be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who have trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys up, with the goal of lowering the monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
“And that’s because you don’t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are purchased.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses with each other," Marek told iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or early next week is not, in Marek's view, decisive.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and that they adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there will be an adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
