The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
MAYBE
The mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, with Czech providers offering virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be able to wait any longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, it is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile service providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a combat statement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile providers, on the other hand, like to reproach the fact that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has often stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, is also obliged to do so.
It’s probably true that a classic provider with its own network doesn’t have a lot of chances anymore (by the way, he probably wouldn’t even find frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile providers had to react.
Before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not have to look for examples for long.
In February this year, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
You don’t need a relatively high cost to build, operate and maintain a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers typically profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to put on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also be adopted in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic no chance, the mobile service providers think
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
For a long time now, the GTS Novera Group has shown its interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecom services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them, we have already made progress in negotiations,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe there will be better times now.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this point, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point out the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press secretary Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> rarely agrees with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds, “T-Mobile’s network will scarcely have a virtual provider coming up by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in such a short term.”
Vodafone pays more attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider to be the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The behaviour of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider is called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something, also proves the long hindsight of the creation of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably from the company T-Mobile when U:fon came on the market.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument as to why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach, however, the Czech regulators are surprised by the absolute lack of interest.
This is not only about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to interfere in economic competition.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, had to do with his very typical attitude to this whole issue.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical providers," says in his response to our request Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
This is more than questionable from an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses their position in the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
Probably, however, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the exact same gasoline price at the gas stations is surely just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence in this matter that indicates an anti-competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they also do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecoms regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if one does not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile service providers act strikingly similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The discharge of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a rather usual trick in the telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enact the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, even though a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS only need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, which are, however, only partly public.
These are usually companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services provide for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selectees.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing is not being discussed with the responsible mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, they do not receive negligible profits from the activities of these companies, but at the same time - unlike the actual virtual providers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
On possible problems, Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile service providers.
That alone, however, would have to be at least strange.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Do mobile providers close their eyes to such an action, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers, they would know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is No Longer the Most Expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant decrease in prices for the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classical providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulators intervened in these moments, which in no way tried to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves in the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competencies in these cases is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flint in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to call than the rest of Europe.
