The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States.
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans were said to have turned to the US president in 1945.
This is evidenced, among other things, by a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter reads.
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia suggests that the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - would expect brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the patronage for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are addressing a state that is foreign to us, that is oppressing and trying to eliminate minorities, and that nothing has contributed to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is supposedly the fear of revenge desires of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a popular decision in the Bohemian Forest to decide whether the inhabitants would become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses, it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Although the Bohemian Germans at least had to guess that their expulsion from the Republic would be negotiated, few of them admitted such an opportunity at all.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Again, others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed in the war as a Budweiser German by the navy at the Baltic Sea.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner of war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, they would get the Czech," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, in his opinion, expected that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
