However, as soon as we turn to other species and intersect with questions of sensation or consciousness in general, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat becomes endangered, it does the same thing as many other animals: it poses dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it is neither measured nor, because of the special hardware, can be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my statements relate to the content of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically easier to access.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than to the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the state of visualization.
What happens to the sensations?
I refer them to the fact that an emotional system like fear is activated in one of its own conscious brain activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the immune system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and in particular humans.
Associated with linguistic nature, fine degrees of sensation result, because with the help of words and grammar, we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others in addition to ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body’s sensation regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in intergenerational sensations.
Purely theoretically, I cannot contradict this, but I consider it to be unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
Does a scab run away in danger if it also feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain stems, scabs do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans: how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even scabs (who knows?), have sensations.
But I didn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I’d rather explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress on the neural level, provided that the same is measured in rats and humans.
Just as I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, so I do not explore sensations, I do not know whether they exist.
You might think this is short-sighted, but I’d rather move forward than constantly running against a wall.
