Avalon Bay announced a few months ago that the small street will be redeveloped and seats will be set up, among other things, for a café to which the company wants to rent space.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the road was first made public during the meeting this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said the company wanted to use the road, but did not necessarily want to own it.
"The main concern of Avalon Bay is to renovate this cul-de-sac and make it a public meeting place," she said, adding that the city itself had proposed the sale.
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for the Department of Building Protection, said it was actually the city’s desire to sell the street and stressed the department’s task was to develop the real estate rather than manage it.
Compared to its colourful neighborhood The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historical impression.
Some believe that the street got its name in 1802, when a large farm that belonged to Philip Minthorne was divided among his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was claimed by no one.
The back door of the CBGB music club, the punk rock monument, which was closed in 2006, opened to the Extra Place and the street is probably best known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of Ramones' "Rocket to Russia" album.
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, manager of the Ramones, who took the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of scrap, lumps and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public land, as modest as it is, should continue to remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged splitter of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Complaints: A Bitter Nostalgic View of the Dying City"), has published part of the City History Conversation on Extra Place, which was published in The New Yorker magazine in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: “Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that even remains dark during the day and is marked by rusted metal doors of the warehouses, closed windows and weekly newspapers flying past rain gutters.”
With a few exceptions, the street looked exactly like this recently on an evening.
A rat ran through the back of the road, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where today there is a more expensive clothing store.
Graffiti was visible on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of out-of-town newspapers.
Some passers-by said they rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a bit.
Fields added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the charm of the street in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in the places that were dark, damp and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch" Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual training.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research fellow in California Studies and senior director of the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully finishing school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among others, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who are only learning English.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Let’s take as an example “Sixth Street Prep,” a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom are only recently in the country, learn English.
Yet in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in mathematics at a good level.
Surprisingly, 93 percent of fourth-year school children were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved by other methods than those preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is practicing the approach of training in an English-speaking environment, which is precisely the point Obama should pay attention to, according to the head of the school, Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in professional lessons.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later, one would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him anymore.
“It works,” she said, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the “Sixth Street Prep” as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-taught students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within his own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s answer uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation targeting “English only.”
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than contempt and trivialize them.
