Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has again shown why some consider him to be the best long-distance runner of all time after breaking his own record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to make it 42.2 kilometers in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one world championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometre to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic Marathon, out of fear that air pollution could exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in the sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie has won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya have moved on long distances, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in 1998 in Berlin with the result 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had cramps in his wad two weeks ago and was therefore unable to train for a week.
Apparently, he was refreshed after a break and did not come back rusted.
"I'm so happy," he told reporters.
“Everything went perfectly.
I resumed training a week ago and had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great."
He has been criticized — particularly in Kenya, Ethiopia’s East African rival — for over-orchestrating his races, avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars in general, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records over the competition.
But this criticism hardly hurts the size of Gebrselassie as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the centre of the route in 1:02:04.
Two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, continued to challenge the pacemaker after the pacemakers had slowed down.
A little more than three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his last start to separate from Kwambai, who came second in 2:05:36, thus improving his best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, completed a remarkable year by showing the seventh fastest result of all time at 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
