She missed the games in Beijing because of problems described as back injuries, but she recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She skilfully planned her run by having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners out first, but overhauled after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the expanses of amusement parks in the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles away from the sparkling, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous Harlem Renaissance author.
And yet the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by taking her into the Florida travel guide, which was produced by the Federal Writers’ Project during the Depression – is and remains in many ways a place of the very special sort.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidature, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open discussion about race relations, many here are still saddened to be watched by outsiders.
“We are very concerned about how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a community member of the city’s oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is on the one hand a stronghold of literature and on the other an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on their guard.
And so the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in word of mouth, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scene of black history and human drama.
Like Oskar in real life as well as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-and-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, though he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and what-also-always fits into hour rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like it."
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
August Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came brewing into the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable clothing style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he swayed in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were stolen.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no big commemoration, no public readings in big style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was submitted when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," Mr. Franklin said.
“There was once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court's demand to enforce integration by calling its decision against the school council in Brown's case "offensive rather than respectful of my race".
Residents today say that although the lifting of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being hugged – I remember – they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the Eatonville Community Protection Nonprofit Group.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You didn’t hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean, there’s a cultural divide,” Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black authors, actors and artists who overcame prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny themselves the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless tomb and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found in the bookshelves, and again made them part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many return for the celebration each January.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
“The plans of a five-lane highway were revitalizing the city, accelerating the whole thing at top speed, arousing real citizen pride,” said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the long-distance road project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
There were more and more train travelers, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named, of course, after Hurston) opened in 2006 on newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is now 90% black.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior approval is necessary and certain things – such as the mural of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work – are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew bigger, a heightened degree of pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw his entire race: beautiful, with all his problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed like any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love of this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who intends to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who he says may need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just pass through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
