Conversation - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and to develop guidelines to prevent another such disaster.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at that time whose goal was to develop a new system for administering blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-canning system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was daunting.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and through work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public’s trust,” she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its establishment on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time we experienced the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of cattle madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which one applies exclusionary measures if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which leads to a degeneration of the brain.
So, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proved without a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes perfect sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow to detect directly in the blood of the donor the presence of the virus itself, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million cans of blood before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case to occur in which HIV was transmitted via a blood can.
I believe that you can feel comfortable these days when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the CEO of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
It was not until last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously,” continues Dr. Décary, before emphasizing that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies in addition to a safe supply.
“Demand is rising because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donation network, to which on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation belong.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent are excluded from blood donation for one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life today is so hectic that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood cans, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed, and frozen before being intermediately stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all of Quebec’s hospitals.
