Free Speech - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a libel lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small, meanwhile, publishing house with the aim of opening a “public transparent debate.”
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers who are paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, by the way, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual arrangement that puts the other side to death and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her views to the public.
Contrary to what is, going on and going on in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually held by exchanging ideas and not by squabbling.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had unveiled its books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent investigative teams that could have brought light to this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand gesture.
Could Mr. Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a “public” debate while disregarding the opinions of this public?
Apparently, this word in the world of the Vice President includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does this primarily because it rejects the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the ‘public debate’ Barrick Gold has just filed a claim to the authors of Noir Canada, in which they no longer use them).
Aside from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom to pursue academic research and truthfinding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and how to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
Wall Street Rescue Action - Democrats and Republicans Understand Each Other
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both Houses of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs on the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public funds used, new provisions to curb the number of houses seized due to defaults, as well as the right to monitor the salaries supported to the executives.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative Judd Gregg, present at the negotiations, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards a deal that will be market-effective," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had accelerated over the past two hours, fearing the impact a new failure would have had on investor sentiment.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two U.S. presidential candidates, who were only late in the negotiations, were more likely to be proponents of the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain provisions of agreement, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes, and those that affect the salaries of executives of state-saved companies.
“When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is not something you could congratulate yourself on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: “I’d like to know the details first, but I hope so.
“The guidelines I’ve read [show] that this is something that we’re all going to have to digest, and that we’re going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at using taxpayers’ money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the placement of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before expanding to other forms of distributed bond (PCAA), and eventually leading to a freeze of financial power and the ruin of banks and monetary institutions.
It was a group of Republican lawmakers who failed their first attempt at unity last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, it is believed to escape the deadlock.
To round out the viewpoints for everyone in Congress, a decree has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to recover its invested capital.
The new plan foresees the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion must be passed by Congress in a re-vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported company, which pay him dividends in the event of profits, and which he can sell again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the option of suspending the detention proceedings in respect of the apartments linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as setting deadlines for repayment and settlements to be paid to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, more votes rose yesterday against this project, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists in asking the taxpayers to pay the cash."
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, leader of a group in Congress called “the caucus of the skeptics,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: We ask Congress not to be pressured and to carefully consider which way to go,” he said.
At the same time, we have once again received proof in Europe that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which has been in great trouble since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the United States’ high-risk real estate.
