The Psychology of Surrender – or Why We’re Ready to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the wrong bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now been able to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play lotto, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the subjects' active brain regions were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which overtaking the opponent plays a significant role.
In addition to many other functions, this region of the brain is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally hired research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were prepared to make higher bets than those in the control or "gain" group.
“These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have, in fact, justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we have now prepared a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travelers are advised to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and refractory stimuli.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year around 1 million people worldwide die from hepatitis B-related, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooists.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to see a doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely recognized, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banishing the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
