What would be the best method to develop new technologies for accident avoidance if not to mimic the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which Nissan Hummeln engineers were inspired to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the autorobot-driven BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers approached the idea of the laser-controlled spacer.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by rotating the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it were not, the autorobot could not react quickly enough to evade the hurdles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered to be inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, evasion, unlike bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While there are infinite possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotary movement, or acceleration and braking, in the autorobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It doesn’t have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it continuously uses only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard over the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to his destination.
