Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events, which, under these new conditions, finally take shape and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to abroad and at the same time manage an immense amount of the wealth of private households living in a single state.
This represents an immediate political problem for governments: namely, how to treat the affected families, who are also a huge mass of voters.
So the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism thus seems to have strayed from itself and lost its right to speak: the clear evidence for this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common way.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of relief funds: since the crisis became more and more serious, only the United States is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overestimated – under certain circumstances – to which no other international organization and no market will be able to resort in a similar way.
That new emphasis on the national-state element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked whole realm, into a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we have to find out at once how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While they can all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
