Medicinal product: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, including in the summer, can cause serious harm to health if they are taken at the same time with certain vital drugs, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor of health at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices in connection with drug use. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: It is enough to virtually eliminate these a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthma drugs, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
The same drug agency had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, and emphasized paying attention to what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or methadone.
It’s not just grapefruit – according to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Michele Carruba, director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano, said: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
Nobel Prize for Economics goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the Bush administration’s biggest critics of economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron Collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more crucial to U.S. history than the assassinations.
A prediction that received a lot of controversy in response and was presented to the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
"I'm surprised and also shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals in the context of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public eye," Krugman explained at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value" but also a basalt analyst with a "very aggressive style, particularly against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration."
Open Office, there is the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more spartanly designed start menu, now finally one of the most basic compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x form is achieved, as well as the support DF for the new version of the document.
Attention was also paid to the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, including the ability to import PDF files into graphic editing modules while preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, you can now also generate "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited multiple times by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a frase to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are just about to publish various OpenOffice features on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is set to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, thus following the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or office.
However, while free-of-charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the program to private households, it is also precisely in the area of business where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized businesses, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-like text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims at extrusion of Excel; Impress, to create presentations as with Powerpoint; Dbase to run databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally, Draw, a graphical module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded with 3 million and 600,000 already reached.
