Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historic cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinema is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-saal complexes in the periphery, means, in the long run, the death of the one-saal cinema in the center. A process that not only seems irreversible and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
It is like losing a friend with whom you have crossed a street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which 20 years ago brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema where there is always a nostalgia, which is always lost in a nostalgic way.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the past five years, the huge amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this mark paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also emerge, but first of all is the preservation of the already existing, because closes a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are ready, instead of the old one a multiplex cinema in the periphery.
And here is still the missing state for the fund of the trade association of external attention: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from an ethical-moral standpoint that the government does not comply with the existing laws.
To maintain the sector, there would be between 16 and 18 million euros a year of needs".
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to fears about the old cinema halls, decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting the traditional cinemas, and this in both the historical center and the Perph.
Among the measures envisaged are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public with regard to local transport: it will be possible to drive to the traffic-restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a welcome initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to align something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was ready to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Mafia group Piromalli..
The accusations of the Calabrian anti-mafia authorities against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia shops, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior intermediary between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew were also caught in handcuffs: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been sentenced to a million euros for involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at the time.
“Disrespecting any kind of moral and legal norm,” the lawyers write, “the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli funds for consulting activities.”
“This made it possible for the mafia group – so the judges – to officially invade the town halls and co-determine the policy of the public administration.”
The president of the Calabrian regional committee Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter connections of local administrations and organized crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the Ndrangheta: heroes who maintain a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow the one of last July with which, according to the police, the Piromalli clan was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also at that time due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration – the local politicians of their municipal offices had been removed.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the UDC, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the May 2006 general election.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He took note of Deputy Interior Minister Marco Minniti, whom he alleged to have invented everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges explain in connection with this morning's arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
From an interrogation operation in connection with the investigation of the case of Dal Torrione, there has been a willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – whereby the measures of public administration became identical with the interests of this clan.
When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up.
It is a non-severing source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now do the world’s big energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be met by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to doubling the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are turning to marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and weighs the possibility of working with us.”
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the US in Alaska and President Bush recently set in motion plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about a growing interest.
Even better technologies are available.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects like those in Portugal and also Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected bows.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using undersea turbines in New York’s East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients are already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Energy Research, the potential that lies in the tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and even waves, and therefore a more reliable source of current.
Tidal energy is precisely what states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 – up to $35 million are already planned for 2009.
